INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '85b709fb-d3ca-4be5-ae3c-27ac6a24cae5',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Docker Image Security — CVE Scanning, Non-Root Users, and Distroless Builds$escape$,
  $escape$Every layer you ADD to a Docker image is an attack surface. Start by scanning with `docker scout cves <image>` (or `trivy image <image>`) to surface CVEs before they hit production — pipe this into CI to fail builds on HIGH/CRITICAL findings.

Running containers as root is the most common misconfiguration. Add a dedicated user in your Dockerfile: `RUN addgroup -S app && adduser -S app -G app`, then `USER app` before `CMD`. This prevents privilege escalation if the container is compromised.

Distroless images (e.g., `gcr.io/distroless/static-debian12`) ship with no shell, no package manager, and no OS utilities — dramatically shrinking the CVE surface. Pair them with multi-stage builds: compile in a full image, copy only the binary into distroless. The final image has nothing an attacker can pivot from. For Go or Rust static binaries, `FROM scratch` goes even further — literally zero base layer. Combine all three: scan in CI, drop root at runtime, ship distroless.$escape$,
  $escape$# Stage 1: build
FROM golang:1.23-alpine AS builder
WORKDIR /app
COPY . .
RUN CGO_ENABLED=0 GOOS=linux go build -o server .

# Stage 2: distroless runtime
FROM gcr.io/distroless/static-debian12:nonroot
COPY --from=builder /app/server /server
# nonroot tag sets USER 65532 automatically
ENTRYPOINT ["/server"]$escape$,
  $escape$bash$escape$,
