INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '94f1c3fa-2bb7-4c50-8fec-fa6d7821ba03',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Docker Swarm — Replica Sets, Service Lifecycle, and Rolling Deployments$escape$,
  $escape$Docker Swarm models deployments as Services, not raw containers. A Service declares desired state — image, replica count, update policy — and the Swarm manager reconciles actual vs. desired continuously. Each replica runs as a Task, which progresses through states: `NEW → PENDING → ASSIGNED → PREPARING → RUNNING → SHUTDOWN → COMPLETE/FAILED`. If a task fails, the manager schedules a replacement on a healthy node automatically.

Replica sets are implicit: set `--replicas 3` and Swarm ensures exactly 3 tasks run at all times. For zero-downtime deployments, configure `--update-parallelism` (tasks updated simultaneously) and `--update-delay` (wait between batches). Setting `--update-failure-action rollback` triggers automatic rollback if the new image fails its healthcheck. You can also trigger manual rollback with `docker service rollback`. Combine with `--health-cmd` in your Dockerfile to gate rollouts on real readiness, not just process start — critical for services with slow initialization like JVM apps.$escape$,
  $escape$docker service create \
  --name api \
  --replicas 4 \
  --update-parallelism 1 \
  --update-delay 15s \
  --update-failure-action rollback \
  --rollback-parallelism 2 \
  --health-cmd "curl -f http://localhost:8080/health || exit 1" \
  --health-interval 10s \
  --health-retries 3 \
  myregistry/api:v2.1$escape$,
  $escape$bash$escape$,
