INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'dbc1eb1e-9ace-42ae-bffa-8a0b384e4931',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Docker Container Autoscaling — HPA, VPA, and KEDA for Event-Driven Workloads$escape$,
  $escape$HPA (Horizontal Pod Autoscaler) scales Docker container replicas by polling metrics-server every 15s against the `resources.requests` defined in your container spec. Set `minReplicas`/`maxReplicas` and a `averageUtilization` target — Kubernetes adjusts replica count accordingly. Simple, but CPU-driven scaling lags behind bursty workloads.

VPA (Vertical Pod Autoscaler) right-sizes container `resources.requests` and `resources.limits` based on observed usage. In `Auto` mode it evicts and restarts containers with corrected values. Critical conflict: HPA and VPA fighting over the same CPU metric will cause oscillation — VPA changes `requests`, shifting HPA's utilization denominator. Run VPA in `Initial` mode alongside HPA, or avoid the combination entirely.

KEDA unlocks event-driven scaling for Docker containers with 50+ scalers: Kafka consumer lag, RabbitMQ queue depth, Redis list length, Azure Service Bus message count. It creates a shadow HPA internally but drives it from external event sources. `minReplicaCount: 0` lets idle consumer containers scale to zero completely — impossible with vanilla HPA. For queue-based worker containers, target lag per replica rather than CPU: 10 unprocessed Kafka messages per container replica is far more responsive than any utilization threshold.$escape$,
  $escape$kubectl apply -f - <<EOF
apiVersion: keda.sh/v1alpha1
kind: ScaledObject
metadata:
  name: kafka-worker-scaler
spec:
  scaleTargetRef:
    name: docker-worker        # Deployment running your container image
  minReplicaCount: 0           # scale-to-zero when queue is empty
  maxReplicaCount: 30
  triggers:
  - type: kafka
    metadata:
      bootstrapServers: kafka-broker:9092
      consumerGroup: worker-group
      topic: job-queue
      lagThreshold: "10"       # 1 replica per 10 unprocessed messages
EOF$escape$,
  $escape$bash$escape$,
