INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '66926fd2-9d70-4560-9af6-d2662299f668',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Docker Swarm Rolling Updates — Zero-Downtime Deploys and Instant Rollbacks$escape$,
  $escape$Docker Swarm's service update mechanism handles rolling deployments natively. When you run `docker service update`, Swarm replaces tasks in batches controlled by `--update-parallelism` (tasks updated simultaneously) and `--update-delay` (wait between batches). Set `--update-failure-action rollback` to automatically revert if a task fails its health check within `--update-monitor` window.

Rollback configuration mirrors update config: `--rollback-parallelism` and `--rollback-delay` control the revert cadence. Swarm stores the previous service spec, so `docker service rollback <service>` instantly reverts to the last known-good configuration without re-pulling an image.

For zero-downtime, pair rolling updates with a HEALTHCHECK in your Dockerfile. Swarm won't mark a task healthy until the health check passes — stopping the rollout from advancing if your new container is broken. Use `--update-order start-first` to spin up the new task before killing the old one, eliminating any gap in capacity during the swap.$escape$,
  $escape$# Deploy with rolling update config and auto-rollback on failure
docker service update \
  --image myapp:v2.1.0 \
  --update-parallelism 1 \
  --update-delay 10s \
  --update-monitor 30s \
  --update-failure-action rollback \
  --update-order start-first \
  --rollback-parallelism 2 \
  --rollback-delay 5s \
  my_service

# Manual rollback to previous spec
docker service rollback my_service$escape$,
  $escape$bash$escape$,
